The '''Slumdance film festival''' was a film festival held in [[Park City, Utah]] in January 1997 by founder [[Brian Flemming]] in a converted [[Mrs. Fields]] cookie factory on Main Street.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.impossiblefunky.com/archives/issue_8/8_skizz.asp?IshNum=8&Headline=Mr.%20Cyzyk%20Goes%20To%20Utah|title=Mr. Cyzyk Goes To Utah|first=Skizz|last=Cyzyk|work=[[Cashiers du Cinemart]]|accessdate=2014-03-24}}</ref><ref name=turan>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=EsIzgmd3CW8C&pg=PA34|title=Sundance to Sarajevo: Film Festivals and the World They Made|first=Kenneth|last=Turan|publisher=[[University of California Press]]|year=2002|isbn=9780520930827|page=34}}</ref>
== History == Slumdance was formed after Flemming's film ''[[Hang Your Dog in the Wind]]'' was rejected by [[Sundance Film Festival]]. Slumdance showed seven features and two shorts. Besides two screening rooms, there was a Build Your Own Festival option that used videocassettes and VCRs.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1997-02-02/news/9702020371_1_slumdance-sundance-two-years-mrs-fields-cookies|title=New Kids On The Block|last=Caro|first=Mark|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|date=1997-02-02|accessdate=2014-03-24}}</ref> Slumdance was set up like a slum, and had a mission area that served free soup, a "Tent City" which was decorated like hobo housing.<ref name=turan/> The converted Slumdance space was 6000 square feet in total.<ref name=turan /> A total of 150 submissions were entered by opening night, and made a press release that stated "Slumdance Stuns Movie World by Existing".<ref name=turan />
The event garnered some media attention, and the parties attracted celebrities including [[Tim Robbins]].<ref name=news>{{cite news | url=http://www.deseretnews.com/article/607476/Slum-fest-wont-hit-Park-City-but-rival-rebels-vie-for-sites.html?pg=all | title=Slum-fest won't hit Park City, but rival rebels vie for sites|last=Vice|first=Jeff|work=[[Deseret News]]|date=1998-01-16|accessdate=2013-05-21}}</ref> A brief interview followed on the Sundance Channel and included what the ''[[Deseret News]]'' called "uncomfortable comments" directed at Sundance mogul [[Robert Redford]].<ref name=news /> An internet based site calling itself the "Slumdance Historical Preservation Society" confirmed that Slumdance would not occur the following year.<ref name=news /> An online-only festival was held in 2000.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.filmthreat.com/festivals/85/|title=What reeks?|author=<!-- Staff -->|work=[[Film Threat]]|date=2000-06-01|accessdate=2014-03-24}}</ref>
